# Nexus Q device-service enablement (systemd preset).
#
# postmarketOS ships a `disable *` catch-all (99-default.preset), and the image
# build runs `systemctl preset-all`. That command STRIPS the enable symlinks of
# any VENDOR unit (one whose unit file lives in /usr/lib/systemd/system) that is
# not explicitly enabled by a higher-priority preset. nexusq-control.service and
# nexusqd.service are vendor units (shipped in /usr/lib by the nexusq-control /
# nexusqd packages), so a hand-placed /etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants
# symlink for them does NOT survive preset-all — it gets disabled again. The
# durable, idiomatic fix (exactly what postmarketos-base does for its own
# services in 90-base.preset) is to declare them enabled here; preset-all then
# (re)creates the enable symlink on every run.
#
# librespot/nq-healthd/nexusq-usb-gadget are "local" units (their unit files
# live in /etc), which preset-all leaves alone, but we list them too so all
# device autostart is declarative and robust against future preset changes.
#
# Priority 95 sorts after postmarketos-base's 90-* presets (no nexusq entries
# there, so no conflict) and BEFORE 99-default's `disable *`, so these enable
# lines win.
enable nexusq-control.service
enable nexusqd.service
enable librespot.service
enable nq-healthd.service
enable nexusq-usb-gadget.service
